  "prompt": "Was Isaac Newton an atheist?",
  "response": "Isaac Newton is not generally considered an atheist. While he is renowned for his contributions to science, Newton also had a deep interest in theology and spent a significant amount of time studying biblical texts. He is known to have had unorthodox religious views, diverging from the mainstream Anglican beliefs of his time, particularly in his rejection of the doctrine of the Trinity. Instead, he is often described as a unitarian or someone with Arian tendencies, which is a belief in the primacy of God the Father over Jesus Christ.\n\nNewton's religious views were complex and private, leading scholars to consider him as a deeply religious man, albeit with beliefs that did not align fully with the established church doctrines of his era.",
